"<p>Note that if you replace $i$, $j$, and $k$ with $m$, $n$, and $p$, the determinant becomes the dot-product of the vector $(m, n, p)$ with the cross-product of the two original vectors.  If $(m, n, p) = (a, b, c)$ or $(m, n, p) = (d, e, f)$, the determinant is zero (any matrix with two identical rows has determinant zero), so the dot product of $(a, b, c)$ or $(d, e, f)$ with the cross-product is zero.  Hence, $(a, b, c)$ and $(d, e, f)$ are orthogonal to their cross-product.</p>\n"	""	""	"2011-11-23T02:24:02.440"	""	""	""	"2"	"2"	"72"	""	"2010-07-20T20:11:12.370"	""	"89"	"92"	""	"2011-11-23T02:24:02.440"	""	"22"	""
