"<p>Exponents are only ""basically"" defined under the natural numbers above zero.  By this I mean, defined as ""iterated multiplication"" the same way multiplication is defined as iterated addition.</p>\n\n<p>The property <code>a^0 = 1</code> only arises when we look at generalizing multiplication to the integers.  We do this by:</p>\n\n<pre><code>a^4 / a^3 = (a*a*a*a)/(a*a*a) = a^1\na^4 / a^3 = a^(4-3)           = a^1\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>And using this, we can say:</p>\n\n<pre><code>a^2 / a^3 = a^(-1) = 1/a\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>and also:</p>\n\n<pre><code>a^2 / a^2                 = 1\na^2 / a^2 = a^(2-2) = a^0 = 1\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>So we say <code>a^0 = 1</code>.</p>\n\n<p>However, notice that these proofs don't have any meaning when <code>a=0</code>, because the whole concept/idea involves fractions, and you cannot have zero be in the denominator.</p>\n\n<p>When we say <code>2^0 = 1</code>, we really mean:</p>\n\n<pre><code>2^(1-1) = 2^1 / 2^1 = 2/2 = 1\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>But we cannot say the same for <code>0^0</code>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>0^(1-1) = 0^1/0^1 = 0/0 = UNDEFINED\n</code></pre>\n"	""	""	"2010-07-20T21:42:02.833"	""	""	""	"5"	"2"	"51"	""	"2010-07-20T21:42:02.833"	""	"144"	""	""	""	""	"135"	""
"<p>A simple approximation</p>\n\n<pre><code>x^2 = 50\n7^2 = 49\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>so the number is around 7.</p>\n\n<p>A even better approximation</p>\n\n<pre><code>(7+x)^2 = 50\n14x + x^2 = 1 \n(14+x)x = 1\n14+x = 1/x\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>This basically shows x is pretty small, and around 1/14, without a calculator, it's not likely you can find what exactly 1/14 is, but at least you know it be smaller than 1/10. 7.1 is a good approximation. (off by less than 0.03)</p>\n"	""	""	"2010-07-20T21:48:27.607"	"1"	""	""	"0"	"2"	"96"	""	"2010-07-20T21:42:38.077"	""	"145"	"96"	""	"2010-07-20T21:48:27.607"	""	"139"	""
