"<p>Unambiguous names for the set of nonnegative integers (0, 1, 2, 3, ...) are <strong>whole numbers</strong>\nUnambiguous names for the set of positive integers (1, 2, 3, ...) are <strong>counting numbers</strong> and $\\mathbb{N}^+$.<br>\nAs other answers (and your own question) indicate, <strong>natural numbers</strong>, or $\\mathbb{N}$, can have different meanings, depending on context. If which usage you mean is not clear from context, you are better off using one of the other terms.</p>\n"	""	""	"2010-07-23T14:53:20.897"	"3"	""	""	"2"	"2"	"73"	""	"2010-07-21T12:56:10.100"	""	"318"	"73"	""	"2010-07-23T14:53:20.897"	""	"283"	""
"<p>A lot of people have mentioned Binet's formula.  But I suspect this is not the most practical way to compute the nth Fibonacci number for large n, because it requires either having a very accurate value of sqrt(5) and carrying around lots of decimal places (if you want to do floating-point arithmetic) or expanding large powers of (1+sqrt(5)) using the binomial formula.  The latter comes out to writing the Fibonacci number as a sum of binomial coefficients.</p>\n\n<p>The following formulas hold, though:\nF(2n-1) = F(n)^2 + F(n-1)^2\nF(2n) = (2*F(n-1) + F(n)) F(n)\nwhich you can find derivations of in <a href=""http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fibonacci_number"" rel=""nofollow"">the Wikipedia article on Fibonacci numbers</a>.  This lets you find F(k), for any k even or odd, in terms of two Fibonacci numbers with approximately half the index.  The result is faster than Binet's formula.</p>\n"	""	""	"2010-07-21T12:59:08.067"	""	""	""	"11"	"2"	"173"	""	"2010-07-21T12:59:08.067"	""	"319"	""	""	""	""	"8"	""
"<p>to show that (p-1)! &equiv; -1 (mod p) without explicitly use group theory, maybe the simplest path is: (the following assumes p is odd, but if p=2 then the result is immediate)</p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>given n &ne; 0, all values n, 2n, ... (p-1)n are different mod p. Otherwise, if hn &equiv; kn (mod p) then (h-k)n &equiv; 0 (mod p) against the hyphotesis that p is prime.</li>\n<li>this means that each n has an inverse mod p, that is for each n there is a m such that mn &equiv; 1 (mod p).</li>\n<li>the equation x<sup>2</sup> &equiv; 1 (mod p) may be written as (x+1)(x-1) &equiv; 0 (mod p); therefore its only solutions are x &equiv; 1 (mod p) and x &equiv; -1 (mod p). For each other number n, an inverse m must exist (because of the pigeonhole principle) but m &ne; n.</li>\n<li>we are nearly done. Let's couple every number from 2 to p-2 with its own inverse. Their product is 1 (mod p), so they don't count in the overall total. 1 does not count either; it remains just p-1, that is -1 (mod p) as requested.</li>\n</ol>\n"	""	""	"2010-07-21T13:00:49.560"	"2"	""	""	"2"	"2"	"89"	""	"2010-07-21T13:00:49.560"	""	"320"	""	""	""	""	"307"	""
"<p>I will quote <a href=""http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_homomorphism"" rel=""nofollow"">Wikipedia</a> on the definition of a ring homomorphism.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>More precisely, if R and S are rings,\n  then a ring homomorphism is a function\n  f : R \u2192 S such that<a href=""http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ring_homomorphism"" rel=""nofollow"">1</a></p>\n  \n  <ul>\n  <li>f(a + b) = f(a) + f(b) for all a and b in R</li>\n  <li>f(ab) = f(a) f(b) for all a and b in R</li>\n  <li>f(1) = 1</li>\n  </ul>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>The last requirement is being relaxed. We can then sub in our <code>f</code>, in this case <code>f(a1)=5a</code> or <code>f(a1)=10a</code> and see if these relations hold. Given that these are small, finite and well understood groups, the problem is easy to solve from here.</p>\n"	""	""	"2010-07-21T13:01:37.873"	""	""	""	"0"	"2"	"123"	""	"2010-07-21T13:01:37.873"	""	"321"	""	""	""	""	"303"	""
