"<p>Note that if</p>\n\n<p>$$ y = \\left(1 - x^7\\right)^{1/5} $$</p>\n\n<p>then </p>\n\n<p>$$ \\left(1 - y^5\\right)^{1/7} = x $$</p>\n\n<p>This means $(1-x^7)^{1/5}$ is the inverse function of $(1-x^5)^{1/7}$. In the graph, one will be the same as the other when reflected along the diagonal line y = x.</p>\n\n<p>Also, both functions </p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>share the same range [0, 1] and domain [0, 1] and</li>\n<li>monotonically decreasing,</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>Therefore, the area under the graph in [0, 1] will be the same for both functions:</p>\n\n<p>$$ \\int_0^1 \\left(1-x^7\\right)^{1/5} dx = \\int_0^1 \\left(1-y^5\\right)^{1/7} dy $$</p>\n\n<p>Grouping the two integrals yield the equation in the title.</p>\n"	""	""	"2010-08-03T09:08:01.803"	"1"	""	""	"32"	"2"	"171"	""	"2010-07-21T14:51:01.790"	""	"345"	"171"	""	"2010-08-03T09:08:01.803"	""	"316"	""
"<p>Similar to the Monty Hall problem, but trickier: at the latest Gathering 4 Gardner, Gary Foshee asked </p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>I have two children. One is a boy born on a Tuesday. What is the probability I have two boys?</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>We are assuming that births are equally distributed during the week, that every child is a boy or girl with probability 1/2, and that there is no dependence relation between sex and day of birth.</p>\n\n<p>His Answer: 13/27. This was in the news a lot recently, see for instance <a href=""http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/more_or_less/8735812.stm"" rel=""nofollow"">BBC News</a>.  (<a href=""http://arxiv.org/pdf/1102.0173v1.pdf"" rel=""nofollow"">Later analysis</a> showed the answer depends on why the parent said that.)</p>\n"	""	""	"2012-05-27T08:25:30.567"	"9"	""	""	"12"	"2"	"115"	""	"2010-07-21T14:52:45.437"	""	"346"	"29642"	""	"2012-05-27T08:25:30.567"	"2010-07-21T14:52:45.437"	"250"	""
