"<p>Yep, the solution by Matiyasevich to Hilbert's tenth problem relies heavily on showing exponentiation is Diophantine.  In other words, the relation R given by $R(x,y,z)$ if and only if $x^y = z$ can be expressed by a polynomial equation $T(x,y,z,w)=0$, such that $R(x,y,z)$ holds if and only if $T(x,y,z,w)=0$ has a solution with $w$ integral.  This is a very difficult and technical result, as well as rather counterintuitive. </p>\n\n<p>Recall that the Fibonacci numbers grow essentially exponentially. One of the lemmas in showing that exponentiation is Diophantine is to show that the Fibonacci sequence (and its variants) are Diophantine.  See the book by Matiyasevich on Hilbert's 10th problem.</p>\n"	""	""	"2010-07-21T20:50:30.707"	""	""	""	"8"	"2"	"536"	""	"2010-07-21T20:50:30.707"	""	"382"	""	""	""	"2010-08-03T18:46:03.740"	"381"	""
