"<p>Differentiation and integration is precisely why it is considered natural, but not just because \n$$\\displaystyle\\int \\frac{1}{x} dx=\\ln x$$</p>\n\n<p>$e^x$ has the two following nice properties</p>\n\n<p>$$ \\frac{d}{dx} e^x=e^x $$</p>\n\n<p>$$ \\int e^x dx=e^x+c $$</p>\n\n<p>If we looked at $a^x$ instead, we would get:</p>\n\n<p>$$\\frac {d} {dx} a^x= \\frac{d}{dx} e^{x\\ln(a)}=\\ln(a) \\cdot a^x$$</p>\n\n<p>$$\\int a^x dx= \\int e^{x\\ln(a)} dx=\\frac{a^x}{\\ln(a)}+c$$</p>\n\n<p>So $e$ is vital to the integration and differentiation of exponentials.</p>\n"	""	""	"2012-07-30T09:19:14.327"	""	""	""	"30"	"2"	"123"	""	"2010-07-27T20:57:59.073"	""	"800"	"19341"	""	"2012-07-30T09:19:14.327"	""	"797"	""
