"<p>Yes, though the word ""dual"" is somewhat questionable.  If you mean is $\\mathbb{P}(\\mathbb{R}^3)$, the standard projective plane, isomorphic to $\\mathbb{P}((\\mathbb{R}^3)^*)$, the projectivization of the dual, then yes, it follows from the isomorphism of vector spaces.</p>\n\n<p>Much more interestingly, the duality allows you to switch points and lines in theorems, such as the <a href=""http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pascal%27s_theorem"" rel=""nofollow"">Mystic Hexagon</a> and <a href=""http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brianchon%27s_theorem"" rel=""nofollow"">Brianchon's Theorem</a>.</p>\n"	""	""	"2010-07-28T01:59:42.910"	"2"	""	""	"3"	"2"	"176"	""	"2010-07-28T01:59:42.910"	""	"893"	""	""	""	""	"892"	""
