"<p>One way that Hopf algebras come up is as the algebra of (real or complex) functions on a topological group.  The multiplication is commutative since it is just pointwise multiplication of functions.  However, in non-commutative geometry you want to replace the algebra of functions on a space with a non-commutative algebra, giving a non-commutative Hopf algebra.</p>\n\n<p>This relates to quantum mechanics because there the analog of the classical coordinate functions of position and momentum do not commute.  Therefore we think of the algebra of functions on a quantum ""space"" as being non-commutative.</p>\n"	""	""	"2010-07-29T18:29:02.197"	"9"	""	""	"3"	"2"	"9"	""	"2010-07-28T13:18:41.627"	""	"960"	"9"	""	"2010-07-29T18:29:02.197"	""	"957"	""
