"<p>Closed points should be thought of as being ""actual points"", whereas non-closed points can correspond to all sorts of different things: subvarieties, ""fat points"", generic points, etc. You might be interested in reading <a href=""http://www.neverendingbooks.org/index.php/mumfords-treasure-map.html"" rel=""nofollow"">this blog post</a> about Mumford's drawing of $\\operatorname{Spec} \\mathbb{Z}[x]$.</p>\n\n<p>One possible way to justify the claim that closed points are the ""actual points"" is the fact that if we have, for instance, a smooth variety over $\\mathbb{C}$, then its <a href=""http://books.google.com/books?id=ZhzXJHUgcRUC&amp;lpg=PA67&amp;ots=aVQoeMkBwc&amp;dq=analytification&amp;pg=PA61#v=onepage&amp;q=analytification&amp;f=false"" rel=""nofollow"">analytification</a> will be a complex manifold. The closed points of the former will then correspond exactly to the points of the latter.</p>\n"	""	""	"2010-07-28T19:44:00.380"	"1"	""	""	"5"	"2"	"263"	""	"2010-07-28T15:54:51.207"	""	"977"	"263"	""	"2010-07-28T19:44:00.380"	""	"942"	""
"<p>Let A and B be two matrices which can be multiplied.<br>\nThen <strong>$\\operatorname{rank}(AB) \\leq \\operatorname{min}(\\operatorname{rank}(A), \\operatorname{rank}(B))$</strong></p>\n\n<p>I proved <strong>$\\operatorname{rank}(AB) \\leq \\operatorname{rank}(B)$</strong> interpreting AB as a composition of linear maps, observing that $\\operatorname{ker}(B) \\subseteq \\operatorname{ker}(AB)$ and using the kernel-image dimension formula. This also provides, in my opinion, a nice interpretation: if non stable, under subsequent compositions the kernel can only get bigger, and the image can only get smaller, in a sort of <em>loss of information</em>.</p>\n\n<p>How to manage <strong>$\\operatorname{rank}(AB) \\leq \\operatorname{min}(\\operatorname{rank}(A), \\operatorname{rank}(A))$</strong>? Is there a nice interpretation like the previous one?</p>\n"	"1553"	"How to prove and interpret $\\operatorname{rank}(AB) \\leq \\operatorname{min}(\\operatorname{rank}(A), \\operatorname{rank}(B))$?"	"2011-07-26T20:04:11.230"	"1"	"4"	"981"	"3"	"1"	"365"	"<linear-algebra>"	"2010-07-28T16:02:17.240"	"3"	"978"	"365"	""	"2011-07-26T20:04:11.230"	""	""	""
